and the NS-Zeit, most papers broaden the scope of the investigation: Protestant-Jewish theological encounters shaped not only antisemitism but also the Jewish Reform movement and Protestant philosemitic post-Holocaust theology; interactions between Jews and Protestants took place not only in the German lands but also in the wider Protestant universe; theology was crucial for the articulation of attitudes toward Jews, but music and philosophy were additional spheres of creativity that enabled the process of thinking through the relations between Judaism and Protestantism. By bringing together various contributions on these and other aspects, the book opens up directions for future research on this intricate topic, which bears both historical significance and evident relevance to our own time.  afunded by Fachinformationsdienst Jüdische Studien  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aJudaismxRelationsxProtestant churchesxHistory. 0aProtestant churchesxRelationsxJudaismxHistory. 4aJudentum. 4aMartin Luther. 4aProtestantismus. 4aReformation.  aHistory of Jewish-Protestant Relations.  aMartin Luther.  aReformation.1 aAriel, Yaakov, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAue-Ben David, Irene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBecke, Johannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Dean Phillip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElyada, Aya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElyada, Aya, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFischer, Lars, econtributor.4ctb